<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Internationals hit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Internationally traded stocks suffered as a stronger pound against the US
dollar affected the value of shares traded in New York.
Comments from a UK Treasury official, who sought to dampen further
expectations of early UK interest rate cuts, helped sterling to rise more
than a cent to breach Dollars 1.50 against the dollar. This left UK stocks
traded as American Depositary Receipts looking expensive.
One ADR trader cited Glaxo and suggested that at least half of the slide in
the pharmaceutical company's shares, which fell 16 to 666p, was the result
of sterling's strength.
Many international stocks also attracted fundamental sellers. Among them,
Reuters Holdings fell 47 to 1825p as a lingering row with the Chicago Board
of Trade over Reuters' Globex dealing system flared up again. Perennially
bullish analyst Mr Brian Newman of Henderson Crosthwaite said the row was a
'storm in a tea cup' and promptly wrote a buy recommendation.
Wellcome drew some attention after it was announced that full results from
last year's big French study on the anti-Aids treatment AZT would be
published shortly in the Lancet medical journal. The shares dropped 22 to
674p.
</TEXT>
