<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Good inflation news is offset
by profit-taking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices ended little changed yesterday after early profit-taking had
overshadowed good news on inflation and a sharp drop in bond yields, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 1.68 at 3,848.63. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 finished a marginal 0.04 up at
474.17, while the American SE composite gained a net 0.50 at 479.87 and the
Nasdaq composite was 1.35 firmer at 786.87.
NYSE volume totalled 310.7m shares, and rises outpaced declines by 1,129 to
938.
The day's big economic news was bullish for financial markets. The
government announced that its index of producer prices rose by only 0.1 per
cent in December, and the 'core' measure of producer price inflation (which
excludes the volatile food and energy components) increased by 0.2 per cent
during the month.
The data were in line with expectations, but still produced a strong
reaction from the bond market, where prices of long-dated government
securities advanced sharply, pushing yields lower.
In the late afternoon the benchmark 30-year bond was up about a point and
the yield was down to 6.169 per cent.
Neither the inflation numbers, nor the bond market's strong performance,
however, was able to breathe life into the equity market, where investors
continued to take profits in the wake of the six-day long new year rally.
However, the profit-taking was not especially heavy, although, as on
Tuesday, some stocks tied closely to the economic cycle (many of which have
risen substantially in recent days) were targeted by the sellers.
Auto makers, which have been in particularly heavy demand lately as
investors bet on another year of improving car and truck sales, retreated.
Ford slipped Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 67 1/2 , General Motors Dollars  1/8 to
59 1/4 and Chrysler Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 59.
Westinghouse Electric eased Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 13 5/8 in volume of
almost 3.9m shares as investors responded to the news that the company will
take charges of Dollars 750m in a restructuring that will cut Westinghouse's
workforce by 6,000. The company also plans to raise Dollars 500m of new
capital to bolster its balance sheet.
After firming early on, American Express ended down Dollars  1/8 at Dollars
30 5/8 after an analyst at Merrill Lynch upgraded his rating on the stock
from 'neutral' to 'above average'.
Fannie Mae moved ahead Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 85 3/8 on news of record
fourth-quarter and annual earnings of Dollars 493.6m and Dollars 1.87bn
respectively.
On the Nasdaq market, leading technology stocks were mixed, with Intel
Dollars 1 5/8 higher at Dollars 68 3/8 , Microsoft up just Dollars  1/4 at
Dollars 85 1/2 and Apple Computer off Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 30 1/2.
Canada
Toronto stocks staged a late-session turnround in extremely heavy trade on a
rebound in bank issues and a continued strong rise in media shares.
The TSE 300 index was finally 7.3 up at an all-time peak of 4,454.7 and
advances led falls by 403 to 390 after volume of 99.5m shares, the fourth
heaviest day's trade on record, and valued at CDollars 1.32bn.
</TEXT>
