<TEXT>
Dayton Hudson, the Minneapolis-based department store operator which has
acknowledged that the holiday periodbrought heavy promotions and sales of
low-margin goods, sent a signal of confidence about its long-term earnings
prospects by raising its dividend, Reuter reports from Chicago.
The 5 per cent increase in the quarterly dividend to 42 cents a share comes
amid a push by the retailer to turn around its suffering Mervyn's division,
analysts said.
California-based Mervyn's has been hard hit by the state's slow economic
recovery, putting a drag on the parent's recent performance, analysts said.
