<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / International Company News: Alcatel profits warning drives
share price down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Alcatel-Alsthom plunged more than 12 per cent yesterday after the
French-based engineering, transport and telecommunications group warned of
lower sales and net profits this year. The shares lost FFr110 to close at
FFr792.
The group said that barring an upturn in market conditions, net profits
would be between 10 and 20 per cent lower than last year, which it said
would be about the same as the FFr7.05bn (Dollars 1.2bn) in 1992. Sales this
year are expected to fall by a smaller proportion than profits.
Most industry analysts had expected a rise of about 5 per cent in net
profits this year. The sharp fall in the share price was also attributed to
the fact that Alcatel-Alsthom previously resisted the effects of European
recession, having increased profits every year since 1986. 'It caught
investors rather off guard,' said one electronics analyst in Paris.
In an interview with Les Echos, the French financial daily, Mr Pierre Suard,
chairman, blamed the expected decline in profits on a deterioration in some
of the group's principal telecommunications markets. He cited Germany, Italy
and Spain as countries where conditions were particularly difficult. He said
the economic situation in Europe had been exacerbated by a 'unilateral
opening of the market', and the failure of other developed economies to
adopt similar measures.
'The ongoing problems in mature markets mean that 1994 will be a difficult
year,' said Mr Andrew Haskins, electronics industry analyst at James Capel
in London. He said Alcatel-Alsthom remained in a strong position to benefit
from the introduction of new technologies.
Mr Suard emphasised the strengths of the group and prospects for expansion.
He said Alcatel had made progress in diversifying its markets, and that the
combined European subsidiaries of the group had increased their exports by
30 per cent last year, and should raise them again by about 20 per cent this
year.
The international telecommunications industry, he said, showed strong growth
potential in areas such as broad-band transmission, mobile communications,
and interactive television. Mr Suard said Alcatel planned to compete for a
third radio-telephone licence to be awarded by the French government.
The Alcatel chairman also expressed confidence in the conclusion of a
Dollars 2bn high-speed railway contract with South Korea. GEC-Alsthom, the
Anglo-French joint venture, has been competing fiercely with a German
consortium for the contract.
</TEXT>
