<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: First Leisure
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After First Leisure's shares fell nearly 40 per cent between May and
November last year, the market could be forgiven for being wary about
yesterday's full-year results. In fact, though margins have fallen, they are
still more than respectable, ranging up to 42.6 per cent in bowling. Despite
a Pounds 67.5m write-down on property, gearing is only 13 per cent, making
First Leisure a picture of health compared with companies such as Rank.
Still, the company has had to make price concessions to keep admissions up
in discotheques. Without the benefit of substantial discounts from its beer
suppliers, margins would certainly have fallen yet more steeply.
A main worry is that bowling, which still accounts for 39 per cent of
operating profits and on which the company made its name, may simply not be
so fashionable any more. This is borne out both by the company's admission
that it may have pushed margins too hard at the height of the bowling boom
in 1992 and by its attempts to stimulate additional interest with trendy
extras in its bowling facilities, the latest being Sega games.
The decision to branch out more or less simultaneously into both bingo and
health clubs suggests the company is groping for new sources of growth. Both
can be adapted to the out-of-town formula which proved successful in
bowling, but bingo is a competitive market and health clubs are expensive to
maintain. While the jury remains out, First Leisure looks more comfortable
on a rating slightly above the market rather than at the 40 per cent premium
at which it peaked last year.
</TEXT>
