<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tonight David Dimbleby adopts the mantle of Tribune Of The People and takes
over the Day/Sissons chair at Question Time promising to ensure that
politicians answer the questions put to them by members of the public. Which
means that today's programme (10.20 BBC1) will be unique. We shall see.
BBC2 begins a magazine series, Big Science (8.00). Each half hour programme
will contain three items. Today's are the Big Bang, gene research, and the
cerebral activity behind the catching of a cricket ball.
What other comedian would dare take 'cogito ergo sum' and turn it into 'I'm
pink therefore I'm spam, you daft old bat' ? It cropped up last week in The
All New Alexei Sayle Show. (9.00 BBC2).
The final programme in Peter Taylor's States Of Terror series investigates
how Army intelligence and MI5 plant agents in Northern Ireland's terrorist
groups (9.30 BBC1).
In Trial And Error David Jessel investigates another alleged miscarriage of
justice: the case of Gary Mills and Tony Poole who were convicted in 1989 of
murder (9.00 C4).
