<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Accountancy Column: Cadbury risks causing indigestion in
boardrooms - Michael Lawrence explains that the report's good intentions are
being translated too bureaucratically
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LAWRENCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
During the last year I made just two public speeches as chairman of the 100
Group of Finance Directors. Yet they have been referred to so often that
many might believe we had conducted a public campaign.
My statements reflected the increasing concern of our members, who are
mainly the finance directors of the FTSE-100 companies, at the direction of
the corporate governance debate and the development of financial reporting
in the UK.
My first speech was concerned with the way in which the Cadbury Report on
the financial aspects of corporate governance was being applied. To counter
some notable corporate failings, Cadbury was concerned with enhancing the
role of non-executive directors, and with higher disclosure standards in
reporting to shareholders.
It is not surprising that there were specific proposals requiring boards to
explain in more detail the internal controls in operation in companies and
to confirm they were 'going concerns'.
The basic thrust of Cadbury is to be commended. What is less useful is that
the committee, as a non-statutory or formally recognised enforcement agency,
had little ability to oversee the implementation of its proposals. It
vaguely left it to 'the accountancy profession and preparers of accounts' to
produce the necessary guidance, although there is no such recognised group.
Equally, a subject such as internal control involves considerations that are
much wider than Cadbury's original terms and in which the accountancy
profession is not readily recognised as having the relevant expertise.
Examples include the attitude of companies to environmental issues and the
control of waste output or of health and safety procedures.
What therefore started life with good intentions has been increasingly taken
over by self-appointed committees which have been able to operate without
adequate control or oversight. As members of all the committees, the 100
Group has been able to see at first hand the over-elaboration taking place,
and the lack of co-ordination - especially between the accounting and the
auditing guidelines.
In addition, because of the informal nature of the whole process, other
pressure groups and bodies began to suggest elaborations of Cadbury, such as
the definition of 'independent' as applied to non-executive directors.
All this has come at a time when boards were already having to grapple with
some fairly radical changes to financial reporting, such as revised
accounting standards, new disclosure formats, a more prescriptive approach
to interim reporting, and efforts by auditors to expand their role whilst
limiting their liability.
One of the reasons I believe that my speech on what I have called 'corporate
overload' attracts so much continuing comment is that it strikes a chord in
many boardrooms. It has been publicly supported by the Confederation of
British Industry, while the need for pacing change has been acknowledged by
government.
It has also been misrepresented in the press as an undue sensitivity by
finance directors to the challenge of future reform. Our basic criticism was
not the development of proper standards of corporate governance, but of
achievable implementation.
A major concern must be to question fundamentally whether the essentially
bureaucratic nature of the disclosure proposals, illustrated by the mountain
of committee and paper-work that is being produced in Cadbury's name, will
lead to the desired objective.
The problem is that sound companies will produce the information required in
a meaningful way but at quite a high cost in management time and audit fees,
whilst those which intend to abuse the system will not be deterred.
Substance has to be distinguished from form.
The required enforcers of the Cadbury recommendations, the London Stock
Exchange and the major investing institutions, have not been represented on
the committees devising the accounting and auditing guidelines being
produced. We believe that Cadbury could, and can, be discredited if the
proposals are not carefully considered and a substantial body of support
developed to forge the way ahead.
We are pleased with the response that we received to our concerns. Sir Ron
Dearing, the out-going chairman of the Financial Reporting Council, called
together those principally responsible for the disclosure proposals and has
sought to ensure that adequate consultation takes place before
implementation. We still believe that some real questioning of the
underlying value of the proposals needs to take place.
The 100 Group actively endorsed a proposed disclosure recommendation in
company annual reports: the operating and financial review. We believe that
more effective corporate governance will be achieved if the boards of listed
companies are required to produce a structured discussion of their financial
results, and of other matters such as Treasury operations.
A statement to shareholders covering financial matters generally, as
contrasted with specific statements on internal control and going concern
alone, seems to us to be a much more valuable approach. Although it may be
criticised as too imprecise, it gives a clear duty to the board to explain
results, and to highlight any areas of potential vulnerability for the
future.
The issue which our other main public statement addresses is the
inter-relationship of the Accounting Standards Board (ASB) and the
International Accounting Standards Committee. A quarter of the FTSE-100
companies are listed on the New York Stock Exchange, and are therefore
required to conform to Securities and Exchange Commission accounting and
disclosure requirements for foreign registrants.
Unless the UK accounting and securities bodies put their weight behind the
development of truly international standards, and we persuade the US
authorities to do likewise, then inevitably the corporate world will
eventually adopt US standards.
The need to gain access the US capital market is very important to large
companies, but we do not wish the potential competitive and cost
disadvantages of producing accounts in several different forms. Moreover, US
standards do not always cater for our different circumstances and, in any
event, are far from perfect as they reflect a substantial history of
American commercial and legal experience.
This issue may seem abstract, but it is likely to have some immediate
effects. For example, we have worked closely with the ASB over the last two
years to develop a sensible approach to accounting for goodwill.
Most large companies, particularly in the service industries, find neither
the immediate write-off of merger premiums nor the alternative of its
subsequent amortisation to be sensible proposals. Whilst they represent
current UK accounting practice, they do not produce balance sheets that
reflect economic reality and can impede takeovers that are otherwise
commercially sensible.
Amortisation produces a double charge against earnings as most companies
will spend money to maintain and enhance goodwill whilst writing it off.
Despite this, my view is that larger UK companies will not support the
alternative of 'ceiling tests' now being considered to avoid amortisation of
goodwill unless there is evidence that other countries will follow.
I believe that developing converging standards across boundaries will be a
major debate during 1994. In setting standards we need to consider the 'art
of the possible' and seek to achieve international consensus.
Michael Lawrence is chairman of the 100 Group of Finance Directors
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8721 Accounting, Auditing, and Bookkeeping Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
