<DOCNO>FT941-15821</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EAMCUACTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Drop in jobless beats forecasts: Government believes fall
shows success of labour market reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
December's drop of almost 47,000 to 2,766,000 in the seasonally adjusted
jobless total was higher than even the most optimistic of forecasts; the
average expectation had been 20,000.
The drop was the ninth monthly fall in 1993, and the fourth consecutive
decrease. The November figure was also revised to show a larger fall -
39,000 compared with 36,000 - than had previously been announced. The
average decline in the three months to December is 46,000.
The unexpectedly speedy fall in unemployment appears to give weight to
government arguments that the labour market reforms of the 1980s have
encouraged employers to be more willing to take on new workers. Mr David
Hunt, employment secretary, said: 'The UK with its flexible, de-regulated
labour market is showing Europe that economic growth can feed through into
more jobs and falling unemployment.'
Many of the jobs being created are part-time, with Department of Employment
figures showing that the number of part-timers increased over the year to
September 1993, while those in full-time employment fell. The proportion of
the workforce in part-time employment in September 1993 was 28 per cent,
compared with 21 per cent in 1983.
After seasonal adjustments, 341,600 joined the unemployment count in
December, down from a revised 341,800 in November. The number of people who
left the register was 376,400, down from 377,200 in the previous month.
The encouraging trend in headline unemployment was backed up by other
encouraging jobs statistics. Figures for the total workforce in employment
in September were revised upwards by 5,000 to 25,005,000, representing a
third quarter rise of 91,000.
The number of unfilled vacancies at Jobcentres rose by 4,500 last month to
145,400, on a seasonally adjusted basis, reaching the highest level since
October 1990. Vacancies have been rising by an average of 6,000 per month
over the last three months. New vacancies totalled 202,900, the highest
number for 3 1/2 years.
The service sector is still the main engine for job growth, with the
manufacturing sector shedding a further 7,000 jobs in November. However the
decline is slowing.
