<DATE>940113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / NatWest confirms 4,000 staff to go
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further evidence of the contraction in the financial services sector came
yesterday as National Westminster Bank confirmed that it expects to lose
about 4,000 jobs this year.
The bank's UK branch network will bear the brunt of the losses, with a
forecasted fall in staff numbers of 3,400. Other cuts will be in support
areas.
Unions expect further job losses to be announced today by other financial
institutions.
On Monday, Barclays announced 3,000 job losses during the next two years -
in a new round of staff cuts.
The Bifu banking union accused the banks of releasing details of their
job-cutting programmes ahead of expected announcements of large profits.
Mr Alan Ainsworth, Bifu assistant secretary, said: 'Big profits seem to be
no bar to cuts in staff, more branch closures and a worse service to the
customer.
'It seems that no matter what the question, NatWest's answer is always
another round of job cuts.' Mr Ainsworth blamed the cuts partly on a desire
among the banks to bring their cost-income ratios down to rates more
comparable with building societies.
NatWest Staff Association is hopeful that there need be no compulsory
redundancies in the branch network.
Mr Stuart Chandler, head of personnel at NatWest, yesterday said that the
bank was committed to reducing job numbers through natural wastage. He said
the use of technology had had an important impact on activities such as
traditional back office processing.
In 1993 4,000 job losses were announced - but only 3,000 jobs were cut. Only
270 of these were compulsory.
Mr Chandler also highlighted the 1,600 new jobs which NatWest plans to
create during the year, in activities such as NatWest Markets, where 200 UK
jobs will be created, and in card processing. NatWest employs about 92,000
staff.
</TEXT>
