<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / London's economy 'reviving steadily'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London's economy is reviving steadily, with strong improvements in business
confidence and domestic and export trade, according to a report published
yesterday.
But the report suggests that the capital's problems are not over. According
to the London Chamber of Commerce and Industry, which interviewed 300 London
companies employing 250,000 people, jobs will continue to be shed in the
early part of this year, particularly in the service sector.
The survey, carried out in the fourth quarter of last year, found that
investment plans had been revised sharply upwards for the next 12 months
with a particular improvement in manufacturing exports.
The chamber says the survey has strengthened hopes for a sustained recovery
in the capital. It says London's financial services sector continued to
grow, with new jobs created.
Business confidence measured in terms of expected profits remains high for
service companies, with the second highest figure recorded since 1988.
Manufacturing shows a similar situation.
The chamber says that while the outlook for jobs remains uncertain, the
slowdown in redundancies has continued.
Quarterly Economic Report and Survey. London Chamber of Commerce, 33 Queen
Street, London, EC4R 1AP. Pounds 12 to members, Pounds 18 to non-members.
