<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Government rules out early cut in base rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday ruled out an early cut in British bank base rates
from the 5.5 per cent level set just before the November 30 Budget.
Speaking after yesterday morning's monthly monetary discussions between the
Treasury and Bank of England, Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary of the
Treasury, said there would be 'no change for the time being' in UK interest
rates.
In an interview with Channel Four's House to House programme, Mr Nelson said
the government was 'content with the present monetary stance'.
There had been a very significant cut in rates during the past year, he
said. That had been of great benefit to industry and would be of 'tremendous
benefit' in the next few months to people whose mortgage rates are changed
annually. The present level of interest rates was satisfactory in terms of
continuing to bear down on inflation. A rate cut was 'unlikely'.
Yesterday's meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, Mr Eddie
George, the Bank governor, and their senior officials lasted less than an
hour. The Treasury's monthly monetary report, prepared for the discussions,
said the latest monthly indicators painted a picture of further economic
recovery and subdued inflation in Britain.
It also noted that inflation expectations had fallen since the December
report. UK producer price inflation remains low while short-term price
expectations as reported by the Confederation of British Industry are at
their lowest recorded level. However, the task of the chancellor and Bank
governor was to look into the future as well. Assessing the path of the
economy is more difficult because of the big tax increases planned for
April.
Officials at the Bank and the Treasury are concerned that the tax increases
due in April could put a break on economic growth.
</TEXT>
