<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Headteachers 'snub inner cities'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Inner city secondary schools are having difficulty attracting headteachers,
a survey by Oxford Brookes University reveals today.
The finding adds to fears of an inner city 'cycle' of social deprivation and
demoralised teachers, raised by Ofsted, the education watchdog, in a report
published last year. Mr John Howson, the author of the Oxford Brookes
survey, said 25 per cent of headships advertised in England and Wales last
year had to be re-advertised. In Tower Hamlets, all nine vacancies had to be
readvertised.
Inner city schools also find it difficult to retain headteachers, according
to Oxford Brookes. Over the last 10 years, nine of the 12 inner London
boroughs have replaced more than 80 per cent of their secondary
headteachers, with Hackney replacing all of them.
Mr David Hart, general secretary of the National Association of
Headteachers, said the results were not surprising. It demonstrated the
increased pressures on inner city schools since exam league tables and the
Ofsted inspection service had been introduced.
</TEXT>
