<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Labour urges stronger SIB role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour last night joined calls for the government to abandon self-regulation
in the financial services industry in favour of a system of direct
regulation by the Securities and Investments Board, David Owen writes.
In remarks released before last night's debate on insider dealing, Mr
Alistair Darling, the party's City spokesman, said the cost of continuing
with a flawed system could not be justified. Self-regulation was a burden on
the industry which had to be paid for by the public.
Mr Darling said the government's silence on the need for a regulatory
overhaul was 'astonishing'.
He said the 'revelation' that up to 500,000 people may have been mis-sold
personal pensions 'should have sent shock waves through the government'.
Effective regulation was not a burden - 'it should be welcomed as a way of
guaranteeing confidence on the part of the public, which would in turn allow
the industry to develop and expand'.
He added: 'What is needed is direct regulation by the SIB with
responsibility to parliament. There is no point in limping on with the
present system when it is increasingly obvious that it is only a matter of
time before a complete overhaul is needed.'
