<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Political Notebook: Back to the 'basics' drawing board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Midsummer madness in January. That was the most optimistic gloss one cabinet
minister could put on the latest furore buffeting Mr John Major. Back to the
bad old days was the more realistic assessment of another colleague.
The odds are that if the government keeps its nerve, the present storm will
blow itself out eventually. But it could rage for some time yet.
A damaging auditor's report on the activities of Westminster City Council
will reinforce the impression that the Conservative party is frequently
indifferent to the traditional values it is now preaching. Downing Street
may well have underestimated the political fall-out.
Lord Howe's appearance yesterday at the Scott inquiry and Mr Major's
evidence to the same body next week will refocus media attention on
Whitehall's less-than-honest handling of arms sales to Iraq.
The tabloid press is determined to keep up the pressure on those ministers
and Tory MPs who, like many of us, have the odd skeleton in the cupboard.
The prime minister may insist that he is not in the business of witch-hunts
 -but witch-hunts sell newspapers.
However absurd have been some (but not all) of the revelations of the past
few days, few in the government doubt the cumulative damage inflicted on Mr
Major. Downing Street has exercised little or no control over events.
No-one, it seems, knows how to run a damage-limitation operation.
So even in the minds of his friends Mr Major emerges once again as an
irresolute leader, a victim rather than a master of events. The old cliche
that the prime minister is 'on probation' has resurfaced in the bars of
Westminster.
His cabinet colleagues have not won any prizes either.
Like the rent-a-quotes on the backbenches, ministers have clamoured for
spots on radio and television to offer their personal and differing
interpretations of what Mr Major means by 'back to basics'.
And for all the prime minister's insistence that his campaign is about
education, law and order and the economy rather than sexual behaviour, the
friends in the cabinet of the moral majority have made the most noise. But
the buck stops at No 10. If his cabinet is undisciplined, it is the prime
minister's job to restore order. He cannot ignore the need for his ministers
to speak with one voice. Nor can he avoid a more detailed explanation of the
moral dimensions of 'back to basics'.
That in itself should not be difficult. Cabinet ministers are at last using
'line-to-take' notes to ensure that they say roughly the same thing when
explaining the policy.
The note omits any detailed exposition of the stance ministers should adopt
towards adultery. But it does not take much imagination to explain that
distinguishing between right and wrong stretches some way beyond the sexual
behaviour of MPs. Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, is expected to do
the job in a speech tomorrow.
Mr Major's problem, though, is one of credibility. Sections of the
Conservative press have decided that whatever he does or says, he is not up
to his job. His enemies on the Tory backbenches speak of him with contempt.
There is an air of resignation in the defences offered by his friends.
The opinion polls reinforce the gloom. Even before the latest furore the
Conservatives' standing was consistently below 30 per cent and Mr Major's
own rating the worst of any post-war prime minister.
The fragile reawakening of self-confidence apparent in the closing weeks of
last year has been stifled. The current unease could be turned to panic by
tax rises in April followed by dismal Conservative performances in the local
and European elections.
Some on the backbenches are already saying that if the government's share of
the vote does not climb above 30 per cent then the prime minister must pack
his bags.
Mr Major cannot be written off. The economy is on his side at last. That
counts. If he can restore a grip, the appeal of 'back to basics' might yet
confound the cynicism of the metropolitan intelligentsia. He is a more
resilient politician than his critics allow.
Most of the bookmakers think it is even money that Mr Major will lead the
Conservatives into the next general election. One or two think his chances
are slightly worse. As of now, most of his colleagues are not offering much
better odds.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
