FT  13 JAN 94 / Anger over curb on council report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday blamed the decision not to publish a report into
alleged electoral manipulation by Conservative-controlled Westminster City
Council on 'bullying' by lawyers acting for Dame Shirley Porter, the
council's former leader.
The government yesterday rejected Labour's calls for publication of the
report. Mr John Magill, the district auditor, announced earlier this week
that his full report, due for release today, would not be published 'for
legal reasons'.
Circulation will be restricted to 12 ratepayers who triggered the inquiry
and about 30 respondents. Other interested parties will receive asummary.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour environment spokesman, contrasted the suppression with
the full publication of district auditors' reports into alleged misuse of
funds by Labour-controlled councils.
Mr Straw said the government should table the report in the Commons to allow
discussion and comment under the protection of parliamentary privilege.
Mr David Curry, local government minister, said publication by the
government would be a misuse of ministerial powers which would amount to
putting pressure on the auditor.
The government is braced for bad news from the report, which will focus on
allegations that the council sold flats in marginal wards to Tory supporters
for political reasons.
