FT  13 JAN 94 / Duncan 'ducks' Commons probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Alan Duncan, the Conser-vative MP under attack over his purchase of a
former council house, was said to have decided to 'duck and run' when the
issue was raised in the Commons last night.
Mr Duncan resigned last week as a minister's parliamentary assistant after
the disclosure that he had lent money to a neighbour, Mr Harry Ball-Wilson,
to buy his house from Westminster City Council at a discount, and that Mr
Duncan had then bought the house from him.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, yesterday expressed
'astonishment' that Mr Duncan, MP for Rutland and Melton, was not in his
place in the Commons, although he had been given notice that the matter was
to be raised. Mr Straw questioned whether it had been right for the
council's 'subsidy' to have been passed on to Mr Duncan when he acquired the
property.
The answer, he said, was dependent on the circumstances in which Mr Duncan
agreed to lend Mr Ball-Wilson, the statutory purchaser, most of the purchase
price.
He also called for an inquiry to establish whether the property should have
been subject to business rates because it had been used as campaign
headquarters for Mr John Major in the 1990 Conservative leadership contest.
Westminster City Council is 'seeking an informal interview' with Mr Duncan
to clarify allegations that he had been using one of his two houses in
Gayfere Street, Westminster, for business purposes. 'If there has been a
material change of use (from domestic to business premises) then we would
want to investigate,' it said.
