<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Cazenove man to head exchange: New chairman says market has
'no divine right to exist'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Kemp-Welch, joint senior partner at stockbrokers Cazenove, and
newly-appointed chairman of the London Stock Exchange, has identified
competition as the main challenge facing the City's central marketplace.
'The main challenge is the competitive element,' he said. 'We are all quite
clear that, politically, competition is the name of the game and I have no
quarrel with that as long as it is fair competition.'
The stock exchange yesterday confirmed that Mr Kemp-Welch will become its
chairman on July 14, following the retirement of Sir Andrew Hugh Smith.
The exchange faces potential competition from companies such as Tradepoint,
set up by a group of former exchange employees, and Reuters Instinet, which
has already gained about 1 per cent of the business formerly transacted on
the New York Stock Exchange.
Unlike the exchange, they are not registered investment exchanges and, as
designated service providers, are subject to less rigorous regulation.
'The stock exchange has no divine right to exist,' Mr Kemp-Welch said. 'It
will only be dominant if it is efficient and cost effective.'
He said that the exchange had much to learn from the US-based Nasdaq, which
has become the world's second most active exchange after only 20 years. 'The
lesson of Nasdaq is what can be achieved from a standing start if you can
provide that efficient, cheap marketplace,' he said.
Mr Kemp-Welch declined to elaborate on any plans to further reduce costs at
the exchange and said that Sir Andrew deserved 'full marks' for having
already achieved significant cost reductions. 'But there is always scope for
further curbing costs,' he said.
He said that another major task would be to ensure that the exchange's Seaq
International system for trading international securities maintained its
role as the dominant exchange for cross-border investment activities.
He said that bringing Seaq into line with new European Union rules would be
an important task.
Mr Kemp-Welch will retire from Cazenove at the end of April. In addition to
his role at Cazenove, he has been a non-executive director of the exchange
and of several other companies including Savoy Hotel.
He will become part of the new senior management team with Mr Michael
Lawrence, the finance director of Prudential, who becomes chief executive on
February 1.
'In an ideal world, the job will require one half-day each week. I will give
it as much time as it needs,' Mr Kemp-Welch said. 'That could turn out to be
a six or seven day a week job, but not all of every day.'
</TEXT>
