<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Transatlantic group wins contract to run Doncaster prison
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A fourth company entered Britain's expanding prison services market
yesterday when Premier Prison Services (PPS) was awarded the contract to
manage the new Doncaster jail.
PPS is a joint venture between Serco, a British facilities management
company, and Wackenhut Corrections Corporation, a US private prison operator
and part of the Wackenhut security group.
Doncaster, the first new town-centre prison built this century, will open by
July and PPS's five-year management contract is worth Pounds 66m. It will be
the most complex prison yet run by the private sector, with convicted and
remand prisoners, young offenders and category A high-security cases among
its 771 inmates.
PPS intends to bring a range of US-style, high-technology security
techniques to its management. Electronic systems will be used to monitor
prisoners, seal off sections of the building in the event of disturbances,
and check on visitors.
The systems will help the company maintain tight staffing levels,
particularly in support services, and its successful bid is based on a
weekly cost per prisoner place of Pounds 295 - low by all standards. The
cost at the new privately managed Blakenhurst prison in Hereford and
Worcester is Pounds 310, one of the lowest.
Mr Derek Lewis, director-general of the Prison Service, said the PPS bid
combined security with positive prisoner programmes. The company intends to
provide 12 hours of purposeful activity for prisoners daily and introduce
anti-bullying initiatives.
Doncaster's governor will be Mr Kevin Rogers, who joined the prison service
as an officer in 1964. He was until recently head of custody at Parkhurst
prison on the Isle of Wight.
PPS joins Group 4, Securicor and UK Detention Services - a consortium of
John Mowlem, Sir Robert McAlpine and Sons and Corrections Corporation of
America - in the prison management and escort services market.
Serco provides management of support services to industry and government
agencies including the Royal Aerospace Establishment, Fylingdales ballistic
missile early warning station in North Yorkshire and the National Health
Service.
Wackenhut operates as a security company in about 40 countries and its
wholly owned subsidiary Wackenhut Corrections Corporation manages prisons in
the US and Australia.
The new Doncaster prison will have about 350 staff and PPS plans a
recruitment job fair in the town.
Dr George Gray, chairman of Serco and of PPS, said industrial relations at
Doncaster were likely to be modelled on the Serco pattern. The company
managed a number of sensitive activities and had lost no time through
industrial disputes. He expected a staff council to be established to
represent employees.
</TEXT>
