<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Rhine damps hopes of the Bonn lobby
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
They call it the Big Hole in Bonn: the huge building site on the banks of
the Rhine where a whole new complex of parliamentary offices is being built,
in spite of the German government's plans to move lock, stock and barrel to
Berlin by the turn of the century.
Now it seems to be not just a big hole, but more of a bottomless pit.
The entire foundations of the DM800m (Pounds 312m) complex have been
devastated by the floods which swept the banks of the Rhine over Christmas.
According to reports confirmed by the construction ministry, the flood
waters actually raised the floor of the building by 70 centimetres, and
caused ominous cracks to appear in much of the concrete piling.
The Bundestag's budget committee yesterday called a halt to the building
programme, and questioned why it was allowed to go ahead at all.
Mrs Irmgard Schwaetzer, the luckless construction minister responsible for
the move to Berlin, has sacked her chief building inspector for failing to
keep her informed, but now faces calls for her resignation.
All this has come on the eve of vital negotiations between Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, the leaders of all the main political parties, and the mayors of Bonn
and Berlin, to decide precisely when and how the great move should take
place.
At their summit meeting tomorrow they also have to settle the most important
question of all: how much the move will cost. Mr Theo Waigel, the finance
minister, who is desperate to contain a swelling budget deficit, told a
party meeting on Tuesday that the costs of moving must be kept to DM20bn -
compared with earlier unofficial estimates of up to DM30bn. His critics
think him hopelessly optimistic.
Ms Ingrid Matthaus-Maier, deputy leader of the Social Democrats in the
Bundestag and a fierce opponent of Berlin, called for a 10-year delay in the
move, saying the figures had been 'massaged'.
Yet any lingering hopes entertained by the vociferous Bonn lobby to delay
the switch of capital have been sorely undermined by the force of the flood
waters on the Rhine.
A spanking new office complex, with a swimming pool, sports hall, and an
underground garage for 1,200 cars, would have been a great temptation for
the members of the Bundestag to stay put beside the Rhine. If the project
has to be abandoned, they may be all too happy to move to the Spree as soon
as possible.
</TEXT>
