<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Court told of Vatican bribes channel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The decisive role of the Vatican bank in channelling alleged bribes in
Italy's political corruption scandal was admitted in court yesterday by one
of the most important intermediaries involved.
Mr Luigi Bisignani, the former head of external relations at the big
Ferruzzi industrial group, admitted he had used the Istituto per le Opere di
Religione (IOR), the Vatican bank, to transfer massive payments from the
company to secret accounts outside Italy.
The IOR achieved public notoriety in the early 1980s when it was implicated
in the collapse of Banco Ambrosiano, the Milanese bank run by Roberto Calvi.
Calvi was later found hanging under Blackfriars Bridge in London.
The payments by Ferruzzi were allegedly made to obtain the support of
politicians for the dissolution of the ill-fated Enimont chemicals joint
venture between Ferruzzi's Montedison industrial arm and the state-owned Eni
energy group.
The 'Enimont affair', in which Ferruzzi allegedly paid a total of about
L150bn (Pounds 59m) in kickbacks, has become one of the most important
strands in the two-year corruption probe. The scandals have cut a swathe
through the Italian political and business establishment and drawn in most
of the country's leading parties.
Making his first public appearance since giving himself up last week, Mr
Bisignani, a former journalist with contacts in the Christian Democrat party
and the Vatican, said he had acted on the instructions of Mr Raul Gardini,
the former head of Ferruzzi who committed suicide last year. Mr Bisignani
was speaking from the witness box at the trial of Mr Sergio Cusani, a
Milanese financier arrested last year as part of the corruption
investigations. Mr Cusani, associated with both Mr Gardini and senior
members of the Socialist party, allegedly acted as a go-between for Ferruzzi
and politicians.
The trial, which opened late last year, is the first big prosecution in the
corruption affair.
Mr Bisignani admitted he had received about L4bn for his efforts to put Mr
Gardini in contact with the IOR. The bank does not normally take outside
deposits. Milan magistrates are trying to ascertain whether part of the
alleged kickbacks ended up in the hands of the large number of
intermediaries, such as Mr Bisignani, who were allegedly involved in the
transactions.
Milan magistrates leading the investigations flew to Luxembourg for
information on alleged transfers from Ferruzzi. Mr Cusani admitted that two
of the Luxembourg accounts identified as having received L52bn in Ferruzzi
money were in his name. While the Milan case, the first in a series of
trials, is expected to last several months, Mr Giuseppe Garofano, the former
top Ferruzzi executive arrested on Tuesday, was interrogated by Naples
magistrates investigating alleged kickbacks in the drugs industry.
</TEXT>
