<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Kiev offered missile-debt swap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A key factor in clinching the deal due to be signed tomorrow between the US,
Russia and Ukraine on the return of Ukraine's warheads to Russia was the
promise by Mr Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian prime minister, to supply
Ukraine with oil and gas below world prices, senior US officials said.
The Russians have also offered to wipe out at least part of Ukraine's energy
debt to Moscow. However, the deal is already causing controversy within
Russia and Ukraine.
Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk confirmed last night after meeting
President Bill Clinton, who had made a stopover visit in Kiev, that he would
go to Moscow to sign the deal. Officials had earlier in the week suggested
he would not initial a full agreement because of insufficient consensus on
details.
Mr Kravchuk was upbeat on prospects that parliament would back him on the
missile issue. He said: 'I hope the parliament will see present-day
realities, see the essence of this agreement and the wishes of the three
states. When they understand this they will support the agreement.'
A senior official of Gasprom, the Russian monopoly gas producer, yesterday
said that if a gas-for-weapons swap and an agreement on debt forgiveness had
been agreed 'at the highest level', Gasprom would have to be compensated,
and the state had no resources to do that. Ukraine owes the Russians
Rbs1,000bn for gas supplies, one-third of their total debt to Moscow.
Mr Kravchuk's willingness to sign the nuclear missile accord, even at the
price of strong domestic opposition, has demonstrated Russia's growing
influence over its Slav neighbour, now racked by hyperinflation, falling
production and energy shortages.
The promise of lower oil and gas prices has also been used to get agreement
between Russia and Belarus on economic union between the two states.
Mr Yeltsin yesterday met Mr Stanislav Shushkevich, the Belarus head of
state, but the official communique issued after the meeting made no mention
of the agreement signed in principle last week by the two countries' prime
ministers and central bankers.
</TEXT>
