<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Howe attacks conduct of Iraq arms inquiry: Scott dismisses
as ludicrous accusation that he was 'detective' and 'inquisitor'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, DAVID OWEN and RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The validity of the Scott arms-for-Iraq inquiry was brought into question
yesterday in a spirited public attack by Lord Howe, the former foreign
secretary.
Appearing as a witness, Lord Howe criticised the conduct of the inquiry in a
lengthy statement, and issued a veiled threat that Lord Justice Scott's
eventual recommendations would be considered invalid by officials and
ministers.
He accused Lord Justice Scott of acting as 'detective, inquisitor, advocate
and judge'. In particular, Lord Howe said he was concerned that witnesses
did not have the right to be represented by counsel or to cross-examine
other witnesses.
Lord Justice Scott described Lord Howe's criticisms as ludicrous and
insisted that no official or minister had complained to the inquiry.
Downing Street emphasised last night that Lord Howe was speaking for himself
and not the government. Lord Justice Scott had to decide on procedures once
the decision on the form of the inquiry had been taken.
However, Lord Howe insisted he had consulted officials and ministers and
said they supported his stand. It also emerged last night that his views are
shared by senior Foreign Office and Downing Street officials. It is not
clear if his attack will undermine the inquiry's conclusions.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, called on Mr John Major, the prime
minister, to make an immediate statement reaffirming his confidence in Lord
Justice Scott.
Mr Smith said Lord Howe's attack was a 'deliberate and clearly premeditated
attempt' to undermine the findings of the inquiry 'only four days before the
prime minister is due to give evidence'.
Earlier Lord Howe had claimed to be speaking largely on behalf of what he
called his former 'flock' at the Foreign Office - officials, ministers, and
intelligence officers.
He said the Scott inquiry had not fully complied with the 'cardinal
principles' for conducting a public inquiry in a fair way.
'Many of those who are looking at these proceedings from outside are bound
to be less enthusiastic to accept conclusions in so far as the cardinal
principles have not been complied with,' Lord Howe said.
The 'principles' referred to by Lord Howe are guidelines for the conduct of
public inquiries laid down by the Salmon royal commission report of 1965.
The commission was set up after strong criticism of Lord Denning's inquiry
into the Profumo affair. It recommended that witnesses should be allowed to
be represented by counsel.
Downing Street would not be drawn on whether the procedures adopted by Lord
Justice Scott were right or wrong. Mr Major would have a better idea of this
after he appears next Monday.
It pointed out that if Lord Justice Scott's investigations had taken the
form of a tribunal of inquiry, the matter would have been sub judice and
subject to reporting restrictions.
In a statement read out by the secretary to the inquiry, Mr Christopher
Muttukumaru, Lord Justice Scott said the inquiry's procedures were
'established with a view to ensuring its efficient conduct while paying full
regard to the need to safeguard the interests of individuals'.
He pointed out that witnesses were allowed to ask for legal assistance and
would be given every opportunity to respond to personal criticism of their
conduct before the final report.
Later, Lord Justice Scott received a vote of confidence from Lord Armstrong
of Ilminster, former head of the civil service, who said he was sure the
judge was conducting the inquiry with 'judicial fairness.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
