<PROFILE>_AN-EAMCUAAJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 94 / Rail sell-off threatens to limit scope of discount fares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rail passengers travelling on cut-price tickets may find themselves paying
more for their journeys or facing a reduced service if present plans for
discount fares after privatisation are adopted.
The full impact of the government's approach to discount fares emerged
yesterday after publication by Transport 2000, a pressure group, of details
of a leaked internal British Rail document. It described promises that rail
companies would honour each other's tickets as 'a bit of a con'.
The companies that take over BR's operations will not be obliged to accept
discounted tickets issued by other companies, Transport 2000 said. It
claimed that eight out of 10 rail tickets sold are discounted Apex, Saver or
Supersaver tickets, although BR said it estimated that at most half of rail
tickets, excluding season tickets, were discounted.
Travellers who buy a discounted return fare might find themselves unable to
take the first train home, because it is run by a rival company, or be
forced to buy another ticket, Transport 2000 said.
'Customers might turn up at the station to find they cannot catch the next
three trains as they are run by another company,' said Mr Barry Doe, a
travel consultant. 'I don't think the public will tolerate that.'
The office of franchise director, which is in charge of selling off BR's
routes, said there had never been any intention to compel the rail operators
to recognise each other's discount fares, although they will be expected to
accept full-fare and season tickets.
Forcing rail companies to accept discount tickets by 'central Diktat' would
undermine the process of privatisation and stifle innovation on fares, it
added. But it does expect the rail operators to reach mutual agreements to
recognise each other's tickets as a way of increasing business.
The leaked BR document, written by Mr Michael Beswick, a senior manager,
said: 'Anyone with knowledge of the BR fares structure will regard
interavailability - being confined to full-fare tickets - as a bit of a con.
It is however probably an income-maximising option for the railway
industry.' BR confirmed that the document was genuine.
Mr Stephen Joseph, Transport 2000 director, said: 'This paper shows that
some of our worst fears about rail privatisation are coming true. Many
travellers will face backdoor fare increases or will be barred from using
some trains. The rail sell-off will make the complex fare structure even
more confusing for passengers.'
A traveller paying Pounds 59 for a Supersaver ticket from London to Glasgow
would have to return with the same railway company or pay a total of Pounds
126 to travel. Transport 2000 plans to ask ministers to have operators agree
cheap fares for every route.
Sea Containers, a shipping company that has expressed an interest in bidding
for the rail franchises, said it expected rail companies to negotiate deals
to accept each other's tickets. 'We would want to develop the principle of
allowing pensioners and others to travel more cheaply off-peak. The future
depends on getting as many people to travel as possible.'
Aslef wins 30% pay rise for Channel train drivers, Page 8
