<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Disease hits Geest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Disease in Costa Rica and market oversupply forced banana group Geest to
issue a profits warning. The shares plummeted on the news, closing 87 down
at 276p. Analysts, concerned at not being warned of the potential damage to
profits of the disease at a round of meetings with the group in December,
rushed to chop profits forecasts.
Strauss Turnbull, which was expecting profits of Pounds 12m, has reduced its
forecast to a Pounds 4m loss. However, some food specialists said the low
share price could encourage a bid, possibly from one of Geest's US admirers.
The profits warning also hit Fyffes, although the stock recovered to close 5
off at 100p.
Television group LWT Holdings receded 23 to 673p as it continued to throw up
barriers to the recent bid by Granada. It predicted a rise of more than 40
per cent in its 1993 profits and expected to pay a final dividend of 14p a
share.
However, one leading securities house is today advising clients to accept
the offer, arguing that Granada will not raise it and there are significant
benefits for LWT shareholders. Granada declined 8 to 572p.
Other perceived television takeover targets Yorkshire Tyne Tees TV and
Anglia moved forward 7 to 188p and 5 to 479p respectively.
Bank shares, among the market's best performers last year as institutions
focused on the benefits that would accrue from falling interest rates and
their impact on the economy, tumbled yesterday in the wake of bearish notes
from two stockbroking houses.
Hoare Govett was said to have wrought the biggest damage, telling its
clients that the sector was 'fully valued on all measures', and weightings
should be 'selectively reduced'. Robert Fleming Securities was also said to
have been advising a bearish stance.
Hoare told clients to use strength in the run-up to February's full year
figures to reduce weightings in HSBC, National Westminster and the Scottish
banks, but remained bullish on long term dividend prospects at TSB and
Barclays.
Lloyds dropped 17 to 620p, Barclays 12 to 597p, NatWest 13 to 597p and HSBC
10 to 916p. Standard Chartered fell 30 to 1179p. There was heavy trading in
TSB, scheduled to announce preliminary figures tomorrow, and the shares
slipped 9 to 250p on turnover of 9.4m.
Eurotunnel fell sharply after surprising the market with a pricing structure
in line with rival ferry operators, against expectations that the Channel
tunnel operator would announce a more competitive pricing structure. The
shares tumbled 17 to 608p, though the poor market trend was said to have
played a part in the slide.
Eurotunnel's pricing structure cheered investors in ferry operator P&amp;O. The
stock was up 12 at best before relinquishing the rise in the poor market
trend to end a net 3 lighter at 630p. Volume was 2.7m.
BAT Industries weakened 17 to 538p after US house Morgan Stanley joined a
downbeat mood surrounding the tobacco to insurance group, downgrading the
stock and lowering its 1993 forecast to Pounds 1.84bn from Pounds 1.88bn.
Reuters Holdings closed 9 higher at 1872p, with NatWest Securities marking
out the company as its favoured stock in the sector. The rise built on sharp
gains last week following talk that Reed International was lining up a bid
for the group. Reed fell 17 to 882p.
Mining group RTZ appreciated 6 to 853p as chart analysts at agency broker
James Capel predicted that the shares could reach 900p soon.
Leading pharmaceutical stocks benefited from US buying on Monday night.
Gains were eroded in late trading, leaving Glaxo just 2 up at 682p, Wellcome
8 ahead at 696p and SmithKline Beecham 'A' a penny harder at 407p.
British Gas declined 4 1/2 to 347 1/2 p as the market fretted about the
company's dividend potential. Adding to the stock's discomfiture was a
cautious note from Hoare Govett, the company's stockbroker.
Courtaulds Textiles climbed 8 to 517p after the group announced that it had
agreed to buy a French weaver and lace manufacturer.
Magellan Industries plummeted 44 to 168p after the swimwear and lingerie
group reported that production problems had hit 1993 sales.
Merchant banks attracted flurries of strong support, with most stocks
advancing to all-time highs as turnover in the stock market and from new
issues continued at record levels.
Hambros forged ahead 15 to equal the stock's peak of 403p, while Kleinwort
Benson, which topped the 1993 mergers and acquisitions league table, moved
up 11 to 607p and threatened its pre-October 1987 high of 615p. Singer &amp;
Friedlander was 3 1/2 firmer at 92p.
Good results from Stakis saw the shares advance 4 to 75p. NatWest Securities
has pencilled in a forecast of Pounds 18m for 1994. The same broker advised
caution ahead of Rank Organisation's results, expected tomorrow. The shares
surrendered 20 to 993p.
Storehouse jumped on the news of a 13 per cent increase in trade in the six
weeks up to Christmas, against analysts' expectations of around 7 per cent.
However, the shares fell back to finish 3 down on balance at 239p as
analysts digested the detail of the statement and worries were expressed
about slightly weaker margins.
Laura Ashley's announcement on trading was better received and the shares
put on 7 at 85p.
Hillsdown Holdings was lifted by its trading statement, the shares gaining 7
at 178p.
Chemical distribution group Ellis &amp; Everard improved 4 to 245p as Hoare
Govett published a buy recommendation and upgraded its 1994 and 1995
forecasts.
</TEXT>
