<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Divisions remain over tropical
timber accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A fourth round of talks aimed at negotiating a successor accord to the 1983
International Tropical Timber Agreement opened in Geneva this week, with
producing and consuming countries still divided over the scope and financing
of the new pact. The present agreement, which has 50 members, expires at the
end of March.
Producer nations argue that temperate as well as tropical timber should be
subject to the conservation disciplines of the new accord, which calls for
all tropical timber exports to come from sustainably managed forests by the
year 2000. They are also seeking extra financial aid to meet this goal.
The two sides are said to have made 'some progress' during last November's
meeting in Japan of the International Tropical Timber Council, which
administers the 1983 pact. The Geneva talks, under the auspices of the
United Nations Conference on Trade and Development, are due to end on
January 21 but may be extended for a third week.
Mr Wisber Loeis of Indonesia, who chairs the negotiations, has proposed a
compromise under which the future accord would essentially be limited to
tropical timber but all member nations would espouse the Year 2000
Objective. The US, Australia and Japan, among temperate timber producers,
have already done so.
</TEXT>
