<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / International Company News: First price manipulation charges
filed by CFTC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Commodity Futures Trading Commission has made its first-ever financial
futures price manipulation filing, charging two former floor traders with
depressing US Treasury bond prices by a full point for their own profit
during 31 minutes of trading in October 1992.
Both former traders are currently subject to criminal indictments by the US
Attorney's office in Chicago and both have already been expelled from CBOT
membership and fined Dollars 2.25m.
The CFTC complaint is the first to address the subject of price manipulation
during the incident, a potentially embarrassing issue which the CBOT was
careful to sidestep in its actions against the traders.
The CFTC found that the two ordered the sale of 13,000 bond futures and the
purchase of 31,000 put options, for a face value of Dollars 4.4bn. At this
point exchange security guards intervened.
The two had less than Dollars 30,000 in trading capital between them and one
had been an exchange member for just one day.
One former trader netted a profit of Dollars 1.5m which was impounded by the
CBOT. The other's positions resulted in Dollars 8.5m of losses which were
absorbed by L. B. Stern, the Chicago firm that guaranteed his account.
</TEXT>
