<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / International Company News: Taiwanese PC maker nearly
doubles profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TAIPEI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Acer, Taiwan's largest personal computer maker, said parent net profits
nearly doubled to an estimated TDollars 1.08bn (USDollars 41m) last year
from TDollars 56m in 1992, Reuter reports from Taipei.
Parent company sales climbed to an estimated TDollars 19.36bn from TDollars
12.24bn Acer said in a statement.
Sales for the entire Acer group rose 67 per cent to TDollars 50bn last year
and group net profits reached a record TDollars 2bn. the company said
without giving group profits for 1992.
Mr Philip Peng, Acer's vice-president, attributed the surge in parent sales
and profits to the introduction of a system under which key computer parts
are exported to overseas factories where final assembly of computers is
carried out.
Profits were also boosted as Acer's joint venture making dynamic random
access memory (DRAM) chips with Texas Instruments started to make money, Mr
Peng said.
Acer's operations in the US and Europe suffered a loss of about TDollars
800m last year but broke even in the fourth quarter.
The parent company obtained TDollars 500m in earnings from land disposals in
1993, compared with TDollars 580m in 1992.
Peng said Acer had set sales targets of TDollars 20bn for the parent company
and TDollars 62.5bn for the group this year.
</TEXT>
