<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / International Company News: Alcoa slides to Dollars 16.7m
deficit in fourth term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Alcoa, the world's largest aluminium producer, reported a loss of Dollars
16.7m, or 20 cents a share, in the fourth quarter, as the US company was
battered by the continued deterioration in prices for primary aluminium and
for aluminium sheet used for beverage cans.
The loss is a reversal of the fourth quarter of 1992, when Alcoa earned
Dollars 49m, or 57 cents a share, before an extraordinary accounting charge.
Including a previously-announced extraordinary charge of Dollars 70.2m, or
80 cents a share, which was taken to cover the cost of severance for 1,600
employees and the closure of some manufacturing operations, Alcoa's loss
totalled Dollars 86.9m, or Dollars 1 a share, in the quarter.
The company's sales fell to Dollars 2.3bn in the quarter, from Dollars 2.5bn
in the fourth quarter a year ago.
For the full year, Alcoa had earnings of Dollars 79.3m or 88 cents a share
before special charges, compared with Dollars 196.3m, or Dollars 2.27 a
share before extraordinary charges in 1992.
Full-year sales were Dollars 9.1bn, slightly below the previous year's
Dollars 9.5bn.
Alcoa had remained profitable through the third quarter while other
aluminium companies were suffering losses.
The company said that it had succeeded in trimming costs, but that the
decline in costs had not kept pace with the precipitous decline in aluminium
prices.
</TEXT>
