<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / International Company News: CSA/Air France dispute
intensifies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM and PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Czech government has stepped up pressure on Air France to sell its
minority stake in CSA to regain control of the cash-strapped Czech national
carrier.
Czech government sources yesterday said financial institutions and two other
airlines had shown interest in CSA. CSA said Czech investors were interested
in buying Air France's stake.
CSA said a letter had been sent to Air France last Saturday asking the
French carrier to sell its stake to Czech subjects. But Air France, which
jointly with the Caisse des Depots, the French state financial institution,
paid Dollars 30m for almost 20 per cent of CSA in 1992, yesterday insisted
it wanted to remain a shareholder in CSA. It said it regarded CSA as a
long-term investment.
Although the Czech government has made it clear it considers the withdrawal
of Air France from CSA as its preferred solution for the Czech airline,
negotiations with the French company and the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), which holds nearly 20 per cent in
CSA, are continuing.
The trial of strength between the two sides rests on Czech demands for
greater control on the airline's board which Air France is resisting.
The Czech government is seeking to modify the June 1992 agreement with CSA's
foreign partners, especially the rule on majority votes for important
decisions at board level. Although the Czech government has a majority of
members on the board, important decisions require the vote of the foreign
partners.
Air France and EBRD have asked for a refund from the Czech government
because they claim the airline was overvalued by about Kcs746m (Dollars 25m)
at the time of the deal two years ago. The French demands appear to have
prompted the Czech government to seek to strengthen its control of the
airline in return for injecting fresh funds in CSA, which is expected to
lose Kcs1.2bn in 1993. However, there have been growing suggestions that the
Czech government is examining the role of foreign investors in large Czech
companies.
</TEXT>
