<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / UK Company News: CU and GRE warn of cuts in bonuses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two more insurers have warned of future cuts in with-profits policy bonus
levels, while maintaining pay-outs at similar levels this year.
Commercial Union has cut pay-outs for shorter term with-profits policies,
but announced a special 5 per cent reversionary bonus for longer term
policies taken out before January 1 1975. A 25 year endowment, taken out by
a man aged 29 paying Pounds 30 a month, maturing this month, would be worth
Pounds 65,599, up 4.2 per cent from last year. A 10-year policy pays Pounds
6,807, down 5 per cent.
Guardian Royal Exchange, which pulled out of the with-profits endowment
market in 1992, continues to be among the lowest payers on existing
with-profits policies.
It has held annual bonuses at last year's level, while raising terminal
bonuses for policies of over 15 years. Its pay-out on a 25-year policy is
Pounds 44,379, up 0.7 per cent from last year, while the 10-year pay-out is
down 1.4 per cent at Pounds 4,952.
</TEXT>
