<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Stakis recovers with Pounds 10.4m -
Restructuring completed: 'we're just a normal boring company now'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stakis, the hotels and casinos group, confirmed its recovery in 1993 by
making pre-tax profits of Pounds 10.4m against a loss of Pounds 47.4m last
time, when the figure was hit by an exceptional provision of Pounds 47.7m.
After two years of restructuring, asset sales and a capital injection, the
Glasgow-based group is now 'a normal company, boring even,' said Mr David
Michels, chief executive.
Thanks to last year's Pounds 28m rights issue and the sale of the nursing
homes, debt fell to Pounds 117m at the October 3 year-end against Pounds
197m, cutting gearing from 77 per cent to 46 per cent.
Sir Lewis Robertson, chairman, said the results owed 'little to the market
and virtually everything to the group's own endeavours.'
Operating profits on continuing businesses increased by Pounds 6m to Pounds
25.6m.
Hotels increased operating profit by Pounds 3.7m to Pounds 19.6m and
achieved an average occupancy rate of 69 per cent. Room rates hardened
slightly.
The company now has 31 hotels following its purchase of a hotel in York for
Pounds 5m.
Casinos increased operating profit by Pounds 3.1m to Pounds 10.9m. Business
was slightly up, particularly in casinos south of Leeds, and the division
enjoyed the benefit of tighter management. Three casinos were acquired in
the Midlands.
Turnover on continuing businesses was Pounds 130.8m in the 53 week period
(Pounds 124m for 52 weeks).
Discontinued businesses had turnover of Pounds 9.47m (Pounds 30m).
Earnings per share came out at 2.81p (losses of 17.38p).
There is a recommended final dividend of 0.55p. The interim dividend was
restored during the year at 0.45p, making a total of 1p (0.45p).
COMMENT
Stakis is now a well-run company. The profit increase is impressive given
that it had little help from the economic upturn, as shown by the modest
turnover growth in the 53 weeks. Since the year end hotel room rates and
occupancy have been rising slightly, and the casinos had a good first
quarter. After attracting a disproportionate amount of media attention for
its troubles Stakis says it wants to be boring. But it would be a pity if
that meant passing up opportunities among the many hotels now on the market.
Analysts are looking for Pounds 17m pre-tax profit in 1994, putting the
shares on a prospective multiple of about 18, and for Pounds 21m next year.
The share price, up 4p to 75p yesterday, already reflects much of the
stock's recovery.
</TEXT>
