<DATE>940112
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Watson &amp; Philip plans store expansion after
21% gain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Watson &amp; Philip, the retail and wholesale food group, plans to expand its
convenience store chain by at least 50 units this year, in a further move
away from its wholesaling roots.
The announcement came as W&amp;P reported a 21 per cent increase in pre-tax
profits for the year to October 29, from Pounds 10.3m to Pounds 12.5m. The
shares leapt 33p to 343p.
The company has gone through several changes in the last year aimed at
repositioning it as primarily a retailer rather than a wholesaler.
Most important was the Pounds 21m acquisition of the Circle K chain last
February.
Circle K's advanced systems were extended into Allday, W&amp;P's existing
convenience store business, and both groups integrated into a reorganised
distribution network.
In October, W&amp;P sub-contracted its Spar and VG supply business to four other
wholesalers in a deal worth Pounds 21m over six years.
The company hopes to add 50 stores to its 316-strong chain by the end of
October, as well as 15 franchise stores, and may increase the expansion rate
to 80 stores next year.
Group turnover increased from Pounds 492m to Pounds 573.9m, thanks largely
to a 36-week contribution from Circle K.
Retail sales more than doubled to Pounds 154.7m, with profits increasing
more than four-fold to Pounds 4.6m.
Turnover at the food service division, which supplies hotels, restaurants
and institutions, increased 3 per cent to Pounds 81m, but profits more than
doubled to Pounds 1.5m as the gross margin benefited from a move out of fast
food supply.
However, profits fell 30 per cent at the cash and carry business to Pounds
2.2m on sales down 8.5 per cent.
Earnings increased 20 per cent to 26p per share, and the proposed final
dividend is 9.9p, lifting the total 7.5 per cent to 14.3p.
COMMENT
The market's enthusiastic response to the news from W&amp;P may be justified.
The company sees a gap in the market for well-run and well-positioned
convenience stores, providing for top-up purchases between superstore
visits, and backed by similar systems and distribution networks to grocery
multiples. The impressive performance of Circle K since its acquisition
appears to support that claim. Convenience store expansion should also make
problems in the cash and carry chain, whose small-business customers have
been decimated by recession and the expansion of multiples and discounters,
an irrelevance. Forecasts of Pounds 14.5m for 1994 put the shares on a
prospective p/e of 12, and at a prospective yield of 5.5 per cent they look
attractive.
</TEXT>
