<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Severe cuts at Westinghouse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Westinghouse, the stricken US conglomerate, announced wide-ranging charges
and lay-offs in an attempt to put behind it a disastrous foray into
financial services during the 1980s.
The company surprised the stock market with the severity of its measures,
which include pre-tax charges totalling Dollars 750m (Pounds 504m), a
planned cut of 6,000 in its workforce over the next two years and halving
its dividend.
It also announced plans to issue Dollars 500m of new capital in the first
half to bolster its flagging balance sheet.
The charges have pushed the company's capitalisation base down to Dollars
1bn compared to Dollars 2.2bn before.
Yesterday's news was the first sign of the drastic surgery promised by Mr
Michael Jordan, the former senior PepsiCo director who was brought in six
months ago to revive the ailing group.
Westinghouse, whose biggest businesses span power generation, broadcasting
and defence, suffered losses put at more than Dollars 5bn after ploughing
money into building junk bond and commercial property operations in the
late-1980s.
Contributing to the charges announced yesterday was Dollars 350m to cover
restructuring costs and the lay-off of 3,400 staff. The world-wide headcount
will come down to around 48,000 by attrition, Westinghouse said.
Also, restructuring and writedowns of businesses which the company plans to
sell will cost Dollars 215m, and it has put aside Dollars 185m to cover the
settlement of legal disputes and environmental clean-up costs.
Westinghouse also adopted a more conservative approach to accounting for
pension liabilities, wiping a further Dollars 255m off its shrunken capital
base.
This has prompted the company to plan an issue of Dollars 500m of preference
shares, which will be converted into ordinary shares at some time in the
future.
Referring to the headway Westinghouse has made in disposing of loans and
other assets over the past year, Mr Jordan said: 'We are essentially out of
the financial services business.' He added that the group's debt had fallen
by Dollars 3.2bn during 1993, to an estimated Dollars 5.2bn at the end of
the year.
Mr Jordan's actions were cautiously welcomed by analysts, who said Mr Jones
had yet to set out his plans for the future.
</TEXT>
