<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / NatWest poised to shed up to 4,000 jobs, say unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Westminster Bank is today expected to become the second high street
bank this week to announce large-scale job cuts.
The announcement, after the 3,000 job losses over two years announced by
Barclays Bank on Monday, will take some of the shine off the monthly
unemployment figures due out today.
National Westminster refused to comment on its job reduction plans and said
any announcement would be made to staff first.
Unions believe the cuts will be larger than those at Barclays and may be as
high as the 4,000 that NatWest announced in February 1993.
The bank did, however, say it was committed to avoiding compulsory
redundancies if possible.
The official jobless total dropped 36,100 to 2,815,900 in November, the
eighth monthly fall last year, leading to government optimism for an
economic revival in 1994.
Falling jobless totals, however, have not reflected the shake-out in the
finance industry, which, according to the Banking, Insurance and Finance
Union, has led to the loss of 100,000 jobs in the past four years.
The union said 3,000 banking and building society branches had closed last
year - 2,000 of them bank branches. It said: 'We feel it is completely the
wrong way for the industry to go because it is alienating the customers.
'Staff are being pushed into accepting performance-related pay rises, often
geared to the sale of products such as insurance policies and pensions, and
leading to customer mistrust.'
The Barclays announcement took total job losses in its five-year programme
to 21,000 up to 1996. It believes there is still scope for voluntary
redundancies, but unions fear that the banks may be running out of other
avenues for job reductions.
National Westminster still has 2,500 branches, more than any of its high
street rivals, but it has been cutting staff in the past three years.
</TEXT>
