<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Model is no quick fix for hospitals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JOHN KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I was interested in the article, 'Production line treatment for
patients' at the Karolinska Hospital, Sweden (January 7).
The suggestion that this experience is unique is incorrect. Many hospitals,
initially in the US but increasingly in the UK, have adopted 'patient
focused' organisational models which are, indeed, derived from approaches to
res-tructuring in the motor industry.
The widespread enthusiasm for these models (including that of the UK
secretary of state for health) should not obscure the fact that the
long-term cost/benefit outcome is ambiguous. The undoubted attractions of
patient focused care should be considered carefully against the potential
risks, which we identified in our report 'Patient focused care - a suitable
case for treatment'. What hospitals have to learn from the motor industry is
that there is no quick fix and no alternative to a sustained commitment to
quality.
John Kelly,
director,
Rawlinson Kelly &amp;
Whittlestone,
16A Hanson Street,
London W1P 7DB
</TEXT>
