<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JAN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Any finance preferable to bank
borrowing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ROBERT J SPENCER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I refer to Brian Warnes's letter (January 4) regarding growth and
companies vowing never to borrow again. This company, 20 years old this
year, recently approached its bank for a loan. The bank's proposed fees
amounted to almost 3 per cent of the sum advanced. It required a charge over
the company's assets, a personal guarantee from me and a mortgage on our
home. It also suggested we should use three sets of solicitors to advise (a)
the company, (b) me, (c) my wife.
In addition, it retained the right to debit the loan account with such
administration charges that it, at its absolute discretion, saw fit and,
finally, it admitted that, no matter what reduction in the loan balance over
time there might be, it would still retain its charge on our home at its
original level.
Given all this we are trying, as Mr Warne suggests, to find a different
source of funds. Perhaps the chancellor's enterprise initiative scheme may
be a way. Notwithstanding this reluctance to borrow, our business is growing
and we have increased employment.
Robert J Spencer,
Fluid Dynamics International,
Finlandia House,
Oxford Road,
Gerrards Cross, Bucks SL9 7RH
</TEXT>
